## Premium Fixture Visual Enhancement Plan

### Architecture Overview

The current SVG canvas renders at model coordinates (millimeters) with a `scale(0.1)` transform, meaning all `vectorEffect="non-scaling-stroke"` strokes render at consistent pixel widths regardless of zoom. The GridRenderer already establishes the pattern for `<defs>` by placing them inside a child component. The FixtureRenderer currently uses flat fills, uniform `#666` outline strokes, and `#888` detail strokes -- everything at strokeWidth 1.

The plan touches three files and introduces one new component for shared SVG `<defs>`.

---

### Part 1: FixtureDefs -- Shared SVG Gradient and Filter Definitions

**New component: `src/renderers/FixtureDefs.jsx`**

This component renders an SVG `<defs>` block containing all gradient definitions and a shared subtle shadow filter. It must be rendered once inside the main `<g>` in SvgCanvas.jsx, before `<FixtureRenderer>`. This follows the same pattern as `<GridRenderer>` which already renders `<defs>` as a child component.

**Shared drop shadow filter:**

A single `<filter>` with id `fixture-shadow` that produces a very subtle offset shadow:

```
<filter id="fixture-shadow" x="-10%" y="-10%" width="130%" height="130%">
  <feDropShadow dx="0" dy="1" stdDeviation="1.5" flood-color="#00000020" />
</filter>
```

Key constraints: Because the SVG is scaled at 0.1, the filter operates in user-space (model mm). The `x/y/width/height` percentages on the filter element handle the bounding box expansion. The `stdDeviation="1.5"` and `dy="1"` values will produce a very subtle shadow at model scale. Since feDropShadow uses model coordinates, at default zoom (0.1) a stdDeviation of 1.5mm becomes 0.15 screen pixels -- essentially imperceptible. To make the shadow visible, use `filterUnits="userSpaceOnUse"` is impractical for varied fixture sizes. Instead, use the `filter` attribute along with `primitiveUnits="objectBoundingBox"` or simply set `stdDeviation` to a larger value like `30` (30mm = 3px at default zoom). However, the cleanest approach given `vectorEffect="non-scaling-stroke"` is:

Actually, the better approach is to skip SVG filters entirely for the shadow and instead render a second polygon behind each fixture, offset by a small amount, with a slightly blurred appearance. But SVG `<feGaussianBlur>` on a duplicated shape in model coordinates works well:

```
<filter id="fixture-shadow" filterUnits="objectBoundingBox" x="-5%" y="-5%" width="115%" height="115%">
  <feGaussianBlur in="SourceAlpha" stdDeviation="2" />
  <feOffset dy="1.5" />
  <feComponentTransfer>
    <feFuncA type="linear" slope="0.12" />
  </feComponentTransfer>
  <feMerge>
    <feMergeNode />
    <feMergeNode in="SourceGraphic" />
  </feMerge>
</filter>
```

Wait -- with `filterUnits="objectBoundingBox"`, the `stdDeviation` is in bounding-box fractions (0 to 1), not pixel or model units. This makes it tricky for varied aspect ratios. The more reliable approach for this codebase:

Use `filterUnits="objectBoundingBox"` with a fractional stdDeviation, or just use the simpler `<feDropShadow>`. Since fixtures vary in size from TV (1200x100mm) to kitchen (2400x600mm), a model-space approach with a generous stdDeviation is better. Let me define the recommended approach clearly:

```jsx
// FixtureDefs.jsx
<defs>
  <filter id="fixture-shadow" x="-20%" y="-20%" width="140%" height="160%">
    <feDropShadow dx="0" dy="30" stdDeviation="25" floodColor="rgba(0,0,0,0.10)" />
  </filter>
  {/* ... gradients below ... */}
</defs>
```

At 0.1 zoom, `stdDeviation="25"` (25mm) renders as ~2.5px blur, and `dy="30"` (30mm) renders as ~3px offset. This produces a subtle, professional lift shadow. At higher zoom levels the shadow scales proportionally, which looks natural.

**Gradient definitions per fixture type:**

Each fixture gets a `linearGradient` for its body fill, replacing the current flat colors. The gradients are subtle -- a light-to-slightly-darker transition that suggests dimensionality without being cartoonish.

| Fixture | Gradient ID | Direction | Stop 1 (0%) | Stop 2 (100%) | Design Rationale |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| kitchenTop | `grad-kitchenTop` | y1=0 y2=1 (top-to-bottom) | `#F0E4CE` | `#D8C5A4` | Warm butcher-block counter, subtle depth |
| toilet | `grad-toilet` | y1=0 y2=1 | `#EAF3F8` | `#C2D8E6` | Clean porcelain white-to-cool blue |
| lavatory | `grad-lavatory` | radialGradient, cx/cy=0.5 | `#EDF5F9` (center) | `#C4D9E8` (edge) | Basin bowl curvature feel |
| table | `grad-table` | y1=0 y2=1 | `#EDE5D8` | `#D0C4B0` | Warm wood grain direction |
| tv | `grad-tv` | y1=0 y2=1 | `#444444` | `#1A1A1A` | Sleek dark electronics |
| sofa | `grad-sofa` | y1=0 y2=1 | `#D8CABC` | `#B8A898` | Upholstery fabric texture direction |

Exact gradient definitions:

```jsx
<linearGradient id="grad-kitchenTop" x1="0" y1="0" x2="0" y2="1">
  <stop offset="0%" stopColor="#F0E4CE" />
  <stop offset="100%" stopColor="#D8C5A4" />
</linearGradient>

<linearGradient id="grad-toilet" x1="0" y1="0" x2="0" y2="1">
  <stop offset="0%" stopColor="#EAF3F8" />
  <stop offset="100%" stopColor="#C2D8E6" />
</linearGradient>

<radialGradient id="grad-lavatory" cx="50%" cy="50%" r="50%">
  <stop offset="0%" stopColor="#EDF5F9" />
  <stop offset="100%" stopColor="#C4D9E8" />
</radialGradient>

<linearGradient id="grad-table" x1="0" y1="0" x2="0" y2="1">
  <stop offset="0%" stopColor="#EDE5D8" />
  <stop offset="100%" stopColor="#D0C4B0" />
</linearGradient>

<linearGradient id="grad-tv" x1="0" y1="0" x2="0" y2="1">
  <stop offset="0%" stopColor="#444444" />
  <stop offset="100%" stopColor="#1A1A1A" />
</linearGradient>

<linearGradient id="grad-sofa" x1="0" y1="0" x2="0" y2="1">
  <stop offset="0%" stopColor="#D8CABC" />
  <stop offset="100%" stopColor="#B8A898" />
</linearGradient>
```

Note: These gradients use `gradientUnits="objectBoundingBox"` (the default), which means they adapt to whatever bounding box the polygon or rect they fill occupies. This works well since fixtures are axis-aligned rectangles (rotation is handled by the `transform` on the group).

**However**, there is a subtlety: the fixture body is rendered as a `<polygon>` with pre-rotated points (the `fixtureOutline` function applies rotation). A gradient with `gradientUnits="objectBoundingBox"` fills the axis-aligned bounding box of the rotated polygon, which will look skewed at non-0/90/180/270 rotations. Since this is an architectural planner where fixtures typically snap to 90-degree increments, this is acceptable. For full correctness, you could apply `gradientTransform="rotate(${rotation})"` but this is unnecessary for the typical use case.

